    parentName: "ul"
  }, "What are the most important obstacles to remove in order to take the company closer to its goals?\nThe list of obstacles to remove should be kept short to make sure the company is focused and aligned.")), mdx("p", null, "When the obstacles are removed or the operating environment changes, strategy is adjusted to reflect the new situation. "), mdx("p", null, "Product development initiatives are seen as bets. Thinking of the initiatives as bets acknowledges that the initiatives are risky by nature. The more sure you are of the outcome of the outcome, that is, the less risky the initiative is, the larger bets you can make."), mdx("p", null, "The job of the product manager is to reduce the risks related to the bets by doing user research. Risks are also mitigated by experimentation - making smaller experimental investments before committing to building the full-blown feature or product, and validating those experiments with the customers. "), mdx("p", null, "Product manager, together with the product team, come up with options that the team can build to "), mdx("h5", null, "The Product Management Process"), mdx("p", null, "Perri introduces a process she calls the Product Kata, a version of the Toyota Kata adjusted to the software development world. Product Kata is a process for continuous development and learning where the product team where the team tackels"), mdx("p", null, "The team selects a goal that describes that is aligned with the strategic intent, and determines what the target metric should be when the goal is fulfilled.\nThe Product Kata is a five step process that is repeated until the goal is reached:"), mdx("ol", null, mdx("li", {
    parentName: "ol"
  }, "Where are we now with our goal?"), mdx("li", {
