  }, "What is the next obstacle preventing us from reaching the goal? These should be small enough to accomplish in a weeks time "), mdx("li", {
    parentName: "ol"
  }, "What step/action can we take to tackle the obstacle?"), mdx("li", {
    parentName: "ol"
  }, "What is the expected outcome of the action?"), mdx("li", {
    parentName: "ol"
  }, "What was the actual outcome and what can we learn from this?")), mdx("p", null, "It's noteworthy that the iterations don't necessarily start with building something. In the first cycles the biggest obstacle might be e.g. lack of product metrics about the phenomenon, and the step to take is to add user tracking to the product. After learning about the user behavior through metrics, the next obstacle might be to understand why users are behaving that way, and the steps to take would be to interview target customers. After these initial discovery steps, one can start building the solution."), mdx("p", null, "The Product Kata is basically the same process that Perri suggest for strategy creation, but applied on a lower organizational level. Product leaders can use it as a coaching tool to help product managers run experiments systematically and efficiently."), mdx("h3", null, "My Impressions"), mdx("p", null, "I believe that one major force keeping companies in the build trap is that an output focused organization feels productive. Everyone is busy developing stuff, features are shipped regularly, and the teams are meeting their (output) goals. The problem obviously is that the goals are set wrongly and the things the teams ship don\u2019t produce customer value. Stepping out of the trap would require a leap of faith from the whole leadership team. The organization would need to slow down on feature development and go into discovery mode to catch up on the research. For a leadership team used to output focused success metrics, this slowing down of feature development will look like the development teams would be losing momentum."), mdx("p", null, "Another force keeping development organizations in the build trap that Perri only briefly touched in the book is the cooperation between product and sales. Salespeople have their quota tied to the sales budgets, and to set the budget, the sales leadership need a product roadmap with sellable features and their release dates. This roadmapping exercise and the commitments it bring pushes the development team towards an output focused, waterfallish working style where shipping in time is a top priority. Solving this puzzle requires a lot of communication, and Perri suggests having a sales roadmap separate from an internal roadmap."), mdx("p", null, "The book assumes a buy-in from the leadership team before any change can happen. I believe that in many traditional companies that are not product-led by nature, more demand for escaping the build trap exists among the product managers. An interesting question left unanswered would be how could a product lead or a similar middle-manager start the transformation process without a strong buy-in from top-management. "), mdx("p", null, "It would most likely require the product lead to push back on the feature wishlists coming from the top, and providing air-cover for the product managers the lead is managing to give them space to do the user research needed. It would most likely take several development cycles before the necessary knowledge would be accumulated and the product teams could start making informed roadmap suggestions to the leadership team. "), mdx("p", null, "Overall, I think Escaping the Build Trap is the best book I've read about how to build a product-led organization. Perri has managed to nail down a very real phenomenon affecting many product development organizations."), mdx("h3", null, "Top quotes"), mdx("h4", null, "Build trap"), mdx("blockquote", null, mdx("p", {
    parentName: "blockquote"
  }, "A build trap is when organizations become stuck measuring their success by outputs rather than outcomes. It's when they focus more on shipping and delivering features rather than on the actual value those things produce.")), mdx("h4", null, "Outputs vs. Outcomes"), mdx("blockquote", null, mdx("p", {
    parentName: "blockquote"
